Journal = {INTERNATIONAL JOURNAL OF MORPHOLOGY},
Year = {2025},
Volume = {43},
Number = {2},
Pages = {494-501},
Month = {APR},
Abstract = {Identification studies progress more accurately and easily after sex
   estimation is realized. Therefore, sex determination is the first step
   in identification studies. The aim of our study is to perform sex
   estimation from the singscapula u machine learning (ML) algorithms with
   parameters obtained from multidetector computed tomography (MDCT) images
   of the Turkish population. The study was performed on MDCT images of 300
   individuals (150 females and 150 males) aged between and 60 years. MDCT
   images of the scapula were imported into the Radiant DICOM Viewer
   program and the following parameters were measured: the maximum length
   of the scapula (SML), the maximum width of the scapula (SMW), the length
   of the scapular spine (SSL), the length of the glenoid cavity (GCL), the
   width of the glenoid cavity (GCW), the distance from the coracoidprocess
   to the inferior angle (CPIA), the distance from the acromion to the
   inferior angle (AIA), the distance from the glenoidtothecavity inferior
   angle (GCIA), the thickness of the lateral margin (LBT), the height of
   the supraspinous fossa (SSH), the height of the infraspinous fossa
   (ISH), the maximum length of the acromion (AML), and the maximum width
   of the acromion (AMW). The obtained data were used for sex prediction
   using ML algorithms. All parameters measured on the scapula were found
   to have significant difference in terms of sex (p<0.05). It was
   determined that the parameters used in sex estimation using MLadmodelsan
   h accuracy rate of 97 \%. Using the SHAP solver of the Random Forest
   algorithm, the parameter of the SSH was found to have greatest
   contribution to accuracy. As a result of our study, we think that we can
   obtain results close to the pelvic y,morphometrwhich is seen as the most
   dimorphic bone in the literature, when sex determination is made based
   on scapula morphometry with analysis. We believe that our study will
   make a great contribution to forensic sciences and literature.},
